questions.explanation:
Without an include guard, the preprocessor pastes the header's content twice into the same file. If the header defines a type (struct, class, enum), the compiler sees two identical definitions and raises a **redefinition error** at compile time.

Example:
```cpp
// player.hh — no guard
struct Player { int hp; };

// main.cpp
#include "player.hh"
#include "player.hh" // pasted again → error: 'Player' redefined
```

The fix is an include guard:
```cpp
#pragma once
struct Player { int hp; };
```
Or the classic `#ifndef` guard.

`this` is a hidden pointer that the compiler passes to every non-static member function. It points to **the specific object on which the method was called**.

```cpp
class Dog {
    std::string name;
public:
    void bark() {
        std::cout << this->name; // 'this' points to the Dog that called bark()
    }
};

Dog d1, d2;
d1.bark(); // inside bark(), this == &d1
d2.bark(); // inside bark(), this == &d2
```

`this` is a pointer to the object, not to the class blueprint or any individual member.

This is called **method chaining**. For `obj.add(1).add(2).add(3)` to work, each call to `add()` must return something you can call `.add()` on again — the same object.

Returning `*this` by reference gives back the original object (not a copy), so the next `.add()` works on the same instance.

```cpp
class Builder {
public:
    Builder& add(int x) {
        // do something with x
        return *this; // return reference to self
    }
};

Builder b;
b.add(1).add(2).add(3); // each call returns b itself
```

If `add()` returned `void`, `obj.add(1)` would return nothing and `.add(2)` would be a compilation error.

questions.text:
What is the error?
```cpp
class Dog {
    std::string name;
public:
    Dog(std::string n) : name(n) {}
};

int main() {
    Dog d("Rex");
    std::cout << d.name;
}
```

questions.explanation:
`name` is declared inside `class Dog` **before** `public:`, so it is **private** by default. Accessing `d.name` from outside the class is a compilation error.

Why the others are wrong:
- B) The initializer list `: name(n)` is perfectly valid C++ syntax for initializing members in a constructor.
- C) `std::string` is a valid type for class members.
- D) It will NOT compile.

Fix: either make `name` public, or add a getter:
```cpp
class Dog {
    std::string name;
public:
    Dog(std::string n) : name(n) {}
    std::string getName() const { return name; }
};
std::cout << d.getName();
```

When a **parameter name shadows a member variable**, the compiler sees the parameter first. Using `this->` explicitly refers to the member.

```cpp
class Circle {
    double radius;
public:
    void setRadius(double radius) {
        this->radius = radius; // 'this->radius' = member, 'radius' = parameter
    }
};
```

Without `this->`, `radius = radius` would assign the parameter to itself — a silent bug.

Why the others are wrong:
- A) `this->` is not required to call private methods from within the class.
- C) You do NOT need `this->` every time you access a member — the compiler resolves it automatically unless there is a naming conflict.
- D) In normal cases it is a style choice, but in the shadowing case it is **necessary**.

When `const` appears **after the parameter list** of a method, it means the method promises not to modify any member variable of the object. This is called a **const member function**.

```cpp
class Person {
    int age;
public:
    int getAge() const { return age; }      // OK: only reads
    void birthday() const { age++; }        // Error: cannot modify member
    void birthday()       { age++; }        // OK: non-const method
};
```

Const methods can be called on `const` objects. Non-const methods cannot.

```cpp
const Person p = {25};
p.getAge();   // OK
p.birthday(); // Error: cannot call non-const method on const object
```

The main benefit of **encapsulation** is control over how data is modified. A setter can check that a value is valid before storing it.

```cpp
class Circle {
    double radius;
public:
    void setRadius(double r) {
        if (r < 0) return; // reject invalid input
        radius = r;
    }
};
```

With a public variable, any code can write `c.radius = -5;` and the object ends up in an invalid state.

Why the others are wrong:
- A) Private/public access has no effect on memory usage.
- B) Public variables do not inherently cause errors in multi-file projects.
- C) Getters/setters are regular function calls — they add a tiny overhead, not a speedup.

questions.text:
Which is the correct constructor?
```cpp
class Circle {
private:
    double radius;
public:
    // constructor here
};
```

questions.explanation:
A constructor has **the same name as the class** and **no return type** — not even `void`.

Why the others are wrong:
- A) `void Circle(...)` — adding a return type makes this a regular function named `Circle`, not a constructor. The compiler will reject it.
- B) `Circle Circle(...)` — `Circle` is not a valid return type here.
- D) `new Circle(...)` — `new` is an operator used to allocate memory, not a keyword for declaring a constructor.

```cpp
class Circle {
    double radius;
public:
    Circle(double r) { radius = r; } // correct
    // or with initializer list:
    Circle(double r) : radius(r) {}  // preferred style
};
```

**C** uses **composition** — `Rectangle` *has a* `Point`. This is the correct relationship: a rectangle is not a point, but it has a position.

Why the others are wrong:
- A) Scatters `x` and `y` as raw doubles. If `Point` already exists and handles position logic, this duplicates that work.
- B) `Rectangle : public Point` uses **inheritance** which implies "a Rectangle *is a* Point". That is semantically wrong — a rectangle is not a type of point.
- D) `double data[4]` hides the meaning. Which index is x? Which is width? This kills readability.

```cpp
class Rectangle {
    Point topLeft;    // composition: has-a relationship
    double width;
    double height;
};
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer composition over inheritance unless a true "is-a" relationship exists.

**Self-assignment** (`a = a`) is rare but valid C++. A naive `operator=` that deletes its own memory first and then copies from `other` will crash when `this == &other`:

```cpp
MyClass& operator=(const MyClass& other) {
    delete[] data;          // frees memory
    data = new int[size];
    std::copy(other.data, ...); // 'other.data' was just freed!
    return *this;
}
```

The guard prevents this:
```cpp
MyClass& operator=(const MyClass& other) {
    if (this != &other) { // skip if assigning to itself
        delete[] data;
        data = new int[size];
        std::copy(other.data, other.data + size, data);
    }
    return *this;
}
```

Note: the check also avoids unnecessary work, but the primary reason is **correctness**, not performance.

A copy constructor must:
1. Have the **same name as the class** (no return type)
2. Take a **const reference** to the same class

Why the others are wrong:
- A) `Num copy(...)` — this is a regular member function named `copy`, not a constructor.
- B) `Num(Num other)` — passing by value would require calling the copy constructor to make the copy, causing **infinite recursion**. The compiler forbids this.
- C) `void Num(...)` — constructors have no return type, not even `void`.

```cpp
class Num {
    int value;
public:
    Num(const Num& other) : value(other.value) {} // correct
};
```

