What is the output?
```cpp
class Cnt {
    int v;
public:
    Cnt(int n) : v(n) {}
    Cnt& operator++() { v++; return *this; }
    Cnt operator++(int) { Cnt old = *this; v++; return old; }
    int get() const { return v; }
};

int main() {
    Cnt a(5);
    Cnt b = a++;
    Cnt c = ++a;
    std::cout << b.get() << " " << c.get();
}
```

questions.explanation:
`std::cout << vec` translates to `operator<<(std::cout, vec)`. This is a **free function** (not a member of `Vec`) that takes the stream as its first argument.

Why `friend` is used: the operator needs access to `Vec`'s private members, so it is declared as a friend inside the class.

Why the others are wrong:
- B) `Vec::operator<<(ostream&)` would be called as `vec << cout` — the operands are reversed.
- C) Returns `void` — this breaks chaining like `cout << a << b`. The stream must be returned.
- D) Returns `Vec&` — the stream object must be returned, not a `Vec`, to allow chaining.

```cpp
class Vec {
    int x, y;
public:
    friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const Vec& v) {
        return os << v.x << " " << v.y;
    }
};
```
